TY  - JOUR
T1  - Seeing Stars: Matthew Effects and Status Bias in Major League Baseball Umpiring
AU  - Kim, Jerry W.
AU  - King, Brayden G
Y1  - 2014/05/05
PY  - 2014
DA  - 2014/11/01
N1  - doi: 10.1287/mnsc.2014.1967
DO  - 10.1287/mnsc.2014.1967
T2  - Management Science
JF  - Management Science
JO  - Management Science
SP  - 2619
EP  - 2644
VL  - 60
IS  - 11
PB  - INFORMS
N2  - This paper tests the assumption that evaluators are biased to positively evaluate high-status individuals, irrespective of quality. Using unique data from Major League Baseball umpires' evaluation of pitch quality, which allow us to observe the difference in a pitch's objective quality and in its perceived quality as judged by the umpire, we show that umpires are more likely to overrecognize quality by expanding the strike zone, and less likely to underrecognize quality by missing pitches in the strike zone for high-status pitchers. Ambiguity and the pitcher's reputation as a ?control pitcher? moderate the effect of status on umpire judgment. Furthermore, we show that umpire errors resulting from status bias lead to actual performance differences for the pitcher and team. Data, as supplemental material, are available at http://dx.doi.org/10.1287/mnsc.2014.1967. This paper was accepted by Jesper S?rensen, organizations.
AB  - This paper tests the assumption that evaluators are biased to positively evaluate high-status individuals, irrespective of quality. Using unique data from Major League Baseball umpires' evaluation of pitch quality, which allow us to observe the difference in a pitch's objective quality and in its perceived quality as judged by the umpire, we show that umpires are more likely to overrecognize quality by expanding the strike zone, and less likely to underrecognize quality by missing pitches in the strike zone for high-status pitchers. Ambiguity and the pitcher's reputation as a ?control pitcher? moderate the effect of status on umpire judgment. Furthermore, we show that umpire errors resulting from status bias lead to actual performance differences for the pitcher and team. Data, as supplemental material, are available at http://dx.doi.org/10.1287/mnsc.2014.1967. This paper was accepted by Jesper S?rensen, organizations.
